    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1982-09-21T08:45:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1982-09-21T08:45:00-05:00" n="2"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d2">
                <head>2. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in Haiti<note n="1"
                        type="source" xml:id="d2fn1">Source: Department of State, Central Foreign
                        Policy File, D820498–0189. Unclassified. Sent through MED Channel. Sent for
                        information to Santo Domingo. Drafted by Washington and approved by
                            <persName corresp="#p_BJL_1">Beahler</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1982-09-21T13:45:00+00:00">September 21, 1982, 1345Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>265172. Subject: <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2">AIDS</gloss> Among Haitian
                    Populations. Ref: Port Au Prince 5108.<note n="2" xml:id="d2fn2">In telegram
                        5108 from Port Au Prince, September 15, the Embassy wrote, “Recent publicity
                        given to occurrence Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome (<gloss
                            target="#t_AIDS_2">AIDS</gloss>) among Haitian population in US and at
                        least two unexplained deaths of Haitians who have gone to US for medical
                        treatment have caused some concern among US Mission personnel here. Would
                        appreciate any facts and guidance <gloss target="#t_MMED_1">M/MED</gloss>
                        could provide our personnel concerning <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2"
                            >AIDS</gloss> and what, if any, precautions we should take.” (Department
                        of State, Central Foreign Policy File, D820478–0613)</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. <gloss target="#t_MMED_1">M/MED</gloss> has contacted Dr. Drotman from <gloss
                        target="#t_CDC_1">CDC</gloss> (Center for Disease Control). He has just
                    returned from Haiti on an investigation on <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2"
                        >AIDS</gloss> (acquired immune deficiency syndrome) among Haitians.</p>
                <p>2. Medical surveillance on this rare disease is inadequate in Haiti, therefore,
                    at this point no one can quantify the exact risk factor of this disease. In the
                    U.S. there has been only 600 cases over the last two years. Dr. Drotman is not
                    aware of a case of <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2">AIDS</gloss> in a non Haitian
                    living in Haiti.</p>
                <p>3. There is no evidence that <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2">AIDS</gloss> can be
                    transmitted via food or water. It is not related to nutritional defects or
                    related to poverty. In review of the cases of <gloss target="#t_AIDS_2"
                        >AIDS</gloss> among Haitians it appears it is not particularly related to
                    how recently they immigrated to the U.S. The hypothesis is that <gloss
                        target="#t_AIDS_2">AIDS</gloss> is transmitted through blood or blood
                    products.</p>
                <p>4. It appears that the U.S. population living in Haiti is at no particular risk.
                    It would be prudent to avoid promiscuous sexual behavior, illegal <gloss
                        target="#t_IV_1">IV</gloss> drug use and to use blood or blood products only
                    in a life saving situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SGP_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Shultz</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
